      • generation

        protected int generation
        The generation number of this trie. This is updated whenever major structural changes are made to the trie that cannot otherwise easily be detected.

        This value is used by sub-classes in implementing prefix sub-tries, which memoize their prefixed root for efficiency, but need to know how to invalidate the value and recompute when necessary. For example, minimal book-keeping is done when the trie is cleared so that the operation can run in constant time. So the generation is incremented when the trie is cleared. A prefix sub-trie will see the change to generation and know to invalidate its memoized root.

      • put

        public V put(java.lang.Iterable<K> key,
             V value)
        Description copied from interface: SequenceTrie
        A convenience method for storing mappings and using non-list collections as keys.

        Note, the iteration order of the given key determines where the value is stored in the trie. Keys made up of the same components but in different orders are considered distinct, unequal keys. So using collections with non-deterministic ordering, like a Set, is not advised because you could query the trie later using an equal set key, but not get the right value due to different iteration order.

        Instead, this method is intended to be used with iterables whose elements represent a finite, ordered sequence, but that may not implement the full List interface.

        Specified by:
        put in interface SequenceTrie<K,V>
        Parameters:
        key - the key, relaxed to an iterable of components instead of a list
        value - the value to associate with the given key
        Returns:
        the previous value associated with the given key or null if no such mapping previously existed

      • prefixMap

        public NavigableSequenceTrie<K,V> prefixMap(K prefix)
        Description copied from interface: SequenceTrie
        Generates a view of all mappings whose keys start with the specified value. The returned map's keys will just be the tail sequences: the specified initial value, which prefixes all of its keys will be omitted.

        Inserting mappings into this prefix map will also insert them into the underlying trie, but with the prefix implied. For example, suppose we have a trie with the following mappings: 

         { "a", "b", "c", "d" } -> 123,
 { "a", "b", "x", "y", "z" } -> 456,
 { "e", "f", "g", "h" } -> 789
        The prefix map, with a prefix of "a", would look like so: 
         { "b", "c", "d" } -> 123,
 { "b", "x", "y", "z" } -> 456
        If the mapping { "m", "n", "o" } -> 1001 were added to the prefix map, it would look like the following: 
         { "b", "c", "d" } -> 123,
 { "b", "x", "y", "z" } -> 456,
 { "m", "n", "o" } -> 1001
        And the main, underlying map would then have the following mappings: 
         { "a", "b", "c", "d" } -> 123,
 { "a", "b", "x", "y", "z" } -> 456,
 { "a", "m", "n", "o" } -> 1001,
 { "e", "f", "g", "h" } -> 789
        Specified by:
        prefixMap in interface NavigableSequenceTrie<K,V>
        Specified by:
        prefixMap in interface SequenceTrie<K,V>
        Parameters:
        prefix - the key prefix
        Returns:
        a view of this map that represents the subset of keys with the specified prefix

      • prefixMap

        public NavigableSequenceTrie<K,V> prefixMap(java.lang.Iterable<K> prefix)
        Description copied from interface: SequenceTrie
        Generates a view of all mappings whose keys have the specified prefix. The returned map's keys will just be the tail sequences: the specified sequence, which prefixes all of its keys, will be omitted.

        This is effectively shorthand for repeated calls to SequenceTrie.prefixMap(Object), like so: 

         SequenceTrie<K, V> result = someTrie;
 for (K value : prefix) {
   result = result.prefixMap(value);
 }

        protected N get(java.lang.Iterable<K> keys)
        Finds the node that represents the given sequence of key elements. This navigates down the trie, finding the next sub-trie that corresponds to the next element in the sequence. If, at any level, no such sub-trie exists, then the given key is not present in this trie.
        Parameters:
        keys - a sequence of key elements
        Returns:
        the node that represents the given key elements or null if it does not exist

      • remove

        protected Reference<V> remove(java.lang.Iterable<K> keys)
        Removes a mapping from the trie. If removal of this mapping creates any empty sub-tries along the path to the removed mapping, they are also removed.
        Parameters:
        keys - the sequence of key elements that identifies the mapping to remove
        Returns:
        an unset reference if the given sequence of key elements did not exist; otherwise a reference set to the value that was associated with the removed keys

      • remove

        protected void remove(N node)
        Removes the mapping for the given sub-trie from this trie. This method then performs clean up to ensure that no empty sub-tries are left in the trie. So a precondition is that the given node has a value.
        Parameters:
        node - the node whose mapping is to be removed from the trie
